    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get the complexity, but it feels like economists who focus on those other factors like automation are sort of hand-waving the obvious problem. if people are getting more money from the government than they can make at a entry-level job, isn't it a pretty settled fact that the rational choice is to stay home? it seems like a massive hole in the logic to pretend that's not the primary driver.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The concept of \"rational choice\" in economics assumes perfect information and constant incentives, which doesn't always apply to real-world labor decisions. People often weigh non-monetary benefits, like job security or the value of time spent on family, which complicate the simple cost-benefit analysis. Furthermore, minimum wage increases or the structure of benefit eligibility can change the *opportunity cost* of working, making the calculus much more nuanced than a simple comparison of benefit vs. entry-level wage.",
      "source": "target",
